<subSubSection pageId="67" pageNumber="66" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="67.[192,1440,195,283]" pageId="67" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,195,219]" pageId="67" pageNumber="66">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon and Hanley" authorityYear="2017" box="[333,528,195,219]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Prodilis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="67" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lindsey">
<emphasis box="[333,528,195,219]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="66">Prodilis lindsey</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a distinctive species recognized by the nearly round body, dorsal color pattern, black legs, and strongly produced prosternum. It bears a superficial resemblance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon and Hanley" authorityYear="2017" box="[1313,1440,228,251]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Prodilis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="67" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ramona">
<emphasis box="[1313,1331,228,251]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="66">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1345,1440,228,251]" italics="true" pageId="67" pageNumber="66">ramona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but is dissimilar from that species in nearly all characters other than dorsal color.
</paragraph>
